AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - EUROPE (19): GERMANY (BRANDENBURG) WILD BOAR, CONFIRMED, OIE
**********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 10 Sep 2020
Source: Federal Research Institute for Animal Health, Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI) press release [edited]
https://www.fli.de/en/news/short-messages/short-message/erster-fall-von-afrikanischer-schweinepest-bei-einem-wildschwein-in-deutschland/


African swine fever virus (ASF) was detected in a wild boar found dead in Brandenburg near the German-Polish border. The Berlin-Brandenburg state laboratory detected specific genome sequences of ASF virus in the samples taken on site. The National Reference Laboratory for ASF at the Friedrich Loeffler Institute (FLI) on the island of Riems confirmed the finding on 10 Sep 2020. This is the 1st case of ASF in Germany.

Bones of a largely decayed carcass were sampled. It can therefore be assumed that the entry took place a few weeks ago.

According to the assessment of the FLI, the risk of the pathogen being introduced into Germany was classified as high. The geographical distance to the last confirmed case of ASF in Poland is only 30 km [18.6 mi]. The proximity to the German-Polish border of about 6 km [3.7 mi] makes an entry by a migrating wild boar likely. An introduction by humans through contaminated food cannot be ruled out. The local veterinary authorities must now take the necessary measures. ASF has been spreading in Eurasia since 2007, reaching in 2014 the eastern border of the EU. ASF is spread over longer distances through human activities such as improper disposal of contaminated food. This led to outbreaks in the Czech Republic and Belgium, both successfully eradicated, supported by the construction of fences. Brandenburg also erected a protective fence against the ASF on its border with Poland, in December 2019.

It is now extremely important for farmers to strictly observe farm biosecurity. This offers the best protection against the pathogen entering farm animal populations. The pig keeping hygiene regulation serves as the legal basis for this.

Examinations of wild boars found dead for the presence of the ASF virus should be intensively undertaken on the national level. Such carcasses should be reported immediately to the authorities. This is usually done by calling. Marking and georeferencing of the site [sending the coordinates] are important. The 'Tierfund-Kataster' (Germany-wide registration of wild animals) free mobile-phone application, at https://www.tierfund-kataster.de/tfk/tfk_erfassung.php, allows convenient reporting and can also be used to send a photograph and coordinates to a remote database.

The disposal of potentially contaminated pig products such as sausage and meat should be applied in a way that excludes access of domestic pigs. Vehicles, clothing, footwear, and equipment that could have been contaminated during hunting, for example, should be cleaned and disinfected.

The Federal German states ("Bundeslaender") are responsible for implementing the protection measures prescribed by the Swine Fever legislation, in particular the establishment of restricted areas and observation areas. Exercises to combat ASF have taken place in some federal states. Regular task force meetings on the current situation and disease control issues are held under the leadership of the Federal Ministry of Food and Agriculture.

Research is being carried out worldwide into the development of a vaccine against ASF, but it will not be used in practice in the foreseeable future. The ASF virus reservoir is the wild boar population; the pathogen is transmitted from pig to pig through blood and droplets. The ASF virus only affects pigs (wild and domestic) and cannot be transmitted to humans. The consumption of wild boar is still safe.

--
