Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The introduction of ASF from wild boar in western Poland into Germany was anticipated for quite some time. Since the remains of the infected animal date back several weeks, additional animals could have been infected or died in the meantime. Their earliest possible detection and testing, and culling of potential contact animals, are warranted.

One of the most important challenges observed in EU countries that have already suffered ASF in wild boar was the difficulty for the veterinary service to keep up with the collection and disposal of all wild boar carcasses for a prolonged period after the detection of the index case. Therefore, as soon as possible after the beginning of the 1st outbreak, other stakeholders need to be involved in the enhanced passive surveillance, and responsibilities need to be shared to control the spread of the disease in wild boar populations.

Furthermore, as the density of the wild boar population is never known exactly and the percentage of wild boar found dead that are notified to the veterinary service is also not precisely known, it is difficult to evaluate the exact impact of the ASF infection on wild boar populations and the effect of the control measures.

Despite the awareness campaigns and information distributed through different channels, some people, especially hunters, were found to still be reluctant to notify authorities of wild boar carcass. Perhaps the reason was the unknown consequences that could have a negative impact on hunting (such as hunting bans, trade restrictions, etc.). Enhanced passive surveillance of ASF in wild boar populations demands for a continuous dialogue between all involved stakeholders and shared responsibility in monitoring and the control of the disease.

The above, and exhaustive, additional information on ASF in Europe's wild boar was included in the Scientific Opinion on 'African swine fever in wild boar', adopted by the European Commission on 12 Jun 2018, published 18 Jul 2018 (EFSA Journal 2018; 16(7): 5344); this paper can be downloaded at https://efsa.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.2903/j.efsa.2018.5344. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Germany: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7765262,10517]
